                <p><strong>Pattern:</strong> Persistent leukocytosis + chronic anemia + very low procalcitonin</p>
                <p>What does this constellation suggest?</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- SLIDE 4 -->
        <div class="slide">
            <h1>CT Chest Findings</h1>
            
            <div class="success-box">
                <h3>Finding #1</h3>
                <p><strong>No acute pulmonary embolism</strong></p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="box">
                <h3>Finding #2: Pneumonia</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>RLL consolidation</li>
                    <li>Scattered bilateral ground-glass opacities</li>
                    <li>Pattern: Pneumonia ± aspiration</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="critical-box">
                <h3>Finding #3: THE CRITICAL OBSERVATION</h3>
                <p style="font-size: 1.2em; margin: 15px 0; font-style: italic;">
                    "Constellation of findings suggestive of <strong>lymphomatous disorder</strong> with 
                    multiple areas of <strong>lymphadenopathy</strong> in chest and upper abdomen"
                </p>
                
                <p><strong>Lymphadenopathy locations:</strong></p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Axillary (bilateral)</li>
                    <li>Mediastinal (multiple stations)</li>
                    <li>Hilar (bilateral)</li>
                    <li>Retroperitoneal</li>
                    <li>Porta hepatis</li>
                </ul>
                
                <p style="font-size: 1.3em; margin-top: 20px;">
                    <strong>= GENERALIZED LYMPHADENOPATHY</strong>
                </p>
            </div>
            
            <p style="text-align: center; font-size: 1.3em; font-weight: bold; margin-top: 30px; color: #e74c3c;">
                The radiologist is telling us: lymphoproliferative disorder
            </p>
        </div>

        <!-- SLIDE 5 -->
        <div class="slide">
            <h1>What Was Actually in the Chart</h1>
            
            <div class="critical-box">
                <h2>Hematology Note from 3 Months Prior (August 2025)</h2>
                <p style="font-size: 1.2em;">Comprehensive note found - 11 weeks before this admission</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="warning-box">
                <h3>Established Diagnosis</h3>
                <p style="font-size: 1.4em; font-weight: bold; color: #e74c3c;">
                    Small Lymphocytic Lymphoma / Chronic Lymphocytic Leukemia (SLL/CLL)
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Diagnosed:</strong> July 2024 (16 months prior)</li>
                    <li><strong>Stage:</strong> Lugano Stage III (above & below diaphragm)</li>
                    <li><strong>Treatment:</strong> Active surveillance (watch & wait)</li>
                    <li><strong>Last hematology visit:</strong> August 2025</li>
                    <li><strong>Due for follow-up:</strong> November 2025 (when admitted!)</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="box">
                <h3>Diagnostic Workup on File</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Flow cytometry (July 2024):</strong> 90% clonal B-cells</li>
                    <li><strong>Immunophenotype:</strong> CD19+, CD5+, CD23+, dim lambda</li>
                    <li><strong>Kappa:Lambda ratio:</strong> 0.01 (markedly restricted)</li>
                    <li><strong>PET CT:</strong> Confirmed Stage III disease</li>
                    <li><strong>FISH studies:</strong> ATM deletion, 13q14.2</li>
                    <li><strong>IGVH:</strong> Non-mutated</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="box">
                <h3>Clinical Status in August (3 months ago)</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Feeling well, no B symptoms</li>
                    <li>Independent in ADLs</li>
                    <li>Active, driving, managing properties</li>
                    <li>Physical exam: 2cm cervical lymph node palpable</li>
                    <li>Labs: WBC 7.34, <strong>Absolute Lymphocyte Count 3.48</strong> (elevated)</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="success-box">
                <p><strong>Follow-up plan documented:</strong> "Return to clinic in 3 months with repeat labs"</p>
                <p><strong>Patient missed this appointment because he was hospitalized</strong></p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- SLIDE 6 -->
        <div class="slide">
            <h1>Hospital Course: Days 2-3</h1>
            
            <div class="success-box">
                <h3>Day 2 - Dramatic Clinical Improvement</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Weaned to room air</strong> - major improvement</li>
                    <li>Afebrile throughout hospitalization</li>
                    <li>Hemodynamically stable</li>
                    <li>No chest pain, SOB, or other symptoms</li>
                    <li><strong>Echo:</strong> EF 60-65%, normal function, no vegetation</li>
                    <li><strong>Troponin:</strong> Flat trend - demand ischemia confirmed</li>
                    <li><strong>Creatinine:</strong> 2.60 → 2.31 (improving)</li>
                </ul>
                <p><strong>Antibiotics:</strong> Ceftriaxone + Azithromycin (Day 1 of 5)</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="warning-box">
                <h3>Day 3 - Laboratory Change</h3>
                <p><strong>Clinical status:</strong></p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Patient wants to go home (same as first admission)</li>
                    <li>SpO2 95% on room air</li>
                    <li>Afebrile, stable vitals</li>
                    <li>No symptoms</li>
                </ul>
                
                <p style="margin-top: 20px;"><strong>Laboratory:</strong></p>
                <table>
                    <tr><th>Test</th><th>Day 1</th><th>Day 3</th><th>Change</th></tr>
                    <tr><td>WBC</td><td>13.61</td><td class="high">14.98</td><td>↑ 10%</td></tr>
                    <tr><td>Hemoglobin</td><td>10.8</td><td class="low">9.9</td><td>↓ 8%</td></tr>
                    <tr><td>Creatinine</td><td>2.60</td><td>2.31</td><td>↓ Improving</td></tr>
                </table>
            </div>
            
            <div class="critical-box">
                <h3>Decision Made</h3>
                <p><strong>Antibiotic Escalation:</strong></p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Discontinued ceftriaxone (after only 1 day)</li>
                    <li>Discontinued azithromycin (after only 1 day)</li>
                    <li>Started piperacillin-tazobactam (Zosyn)</li>
                </ul>
                <p style="margin-top: 15px;"><strong>Rationale:</strong> WBC trending upward</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- SLIDE 7 -->
        <div class="slide">
            <h1>Clinical Reasoning Challenge</h1>
            
            <div class="warning-box">
                <h3>When Lab and Clinical Picture Diverge - Which Do You Trust?</h3>
            </div>
            
            <div class="box">
                <h3>Clinical Picture (Day 3)</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>✓ Weaned to room air</li>
                    <li>✓ Afebrile × 72 hours</li>
                    <li>✓ Hemodynamically stable</li>
                    <li>✓ No respiratory distress</li>
                    <li>✓ Creatinine improving</li>
                    <li>✓ No overnight events</li>
                    <li>✓ Patient feels well enough to demand discharge</li>
                </ul>
                <p style="margin-top: 15px; font-weight: bold;">IDSA Guidelines: Clinical stability = treatment success</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="box">
                <h3>Laboratory Findings</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>WBC 13.61 → 14.98 (↑10%)</li>
                    <li>No differential ordered</li>
                    <li>Blood cultures negative</li>
                    <li>Procalcitonin was 0.07 (very low)</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="critical-box">
                <h3>Understanding WBC in CLL</h3>
                <p><strong>If CLL diagnosis had been recognized:</strong></p>
                <ul>
                    <li>WBC elevation represents <strong>baseline lymphocytosis from CLL</strong>, NOT treatment failure</li>
                    <li>From August labs: Absolute Lymphocyte Count was 3.48 K/µL (elevated baseline)</li>
                    <li>Should have ordered <strong>CBC with differential</strong> to distinguish:
                        <ul>
                            <li>Lymphocytes (from CLL - baseline elevation)</li>
                            <li>vs Neutrophils (from infection)</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                </ul>
                <p style="margin-top: 20px; font-weight: bold; font-size: 1.2em;">
                    Total WBC alone is insufficient - ALWAYS check differential
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- SLIDE 8 -->
        <div class="slide">
            <h1>Teaching Point: Systematic Chart Review</h1>
            
            <div class="box">
                <h2>The SEARCH Mnemonic</h2>
                <p style="font-size: 1.2em; margin-bottom: 20px;">Systematic approach to prevent missing critical information</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="box">
                <h3>S - SEARCH Systematically</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Use EMR keyword search: "biopsy," "pathology," "flow cytometry," "malignancy," "hematology"</li>
                    <li>Search for specialty referrals</li>
                    <li>Don't rely solely on recent notes or patient recall</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="box">
                <h3>E - EXAMINE Problem List</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Review both active AND inactive diagnoses</li>
                    <li>Question why chronic conditions might be absent</li>
                    <li>Look for diagnoses that "disappeared"</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="box">
                <h3>A - ASK Specific Questions</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>"Have you ever had a biopsy of a lymph node?"</li>
                    <li>"Do you see a cancer doctor or blood specialist?"</li>
                    <li>"What medications did you used to take that you stopped?"</li>
                    <li>For dementia patients: Obtain collateral from family</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="box">
                <h3>R - REVIEW Prior Imaging</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Compare current findings to prior studies</li>
                    <li>Distinguish NEW from CHRONIC findings</li>
                    <li>Chronicity completely changes management</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="box">
                <h3>C - CHECK Medications</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Prophylactic antibiotics → immunosuppression?</li>
                    <li>Iron supplements → chronic anemia, why?</li>
                    <li>Review discontinued medications</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="box">
                <h3>H - HOSPITAL/Specialty Records</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Search for pathology reports (past 2-3 years)</li>
                    <li>Review discharge summaries</li>
                    <li>Read specialty notes (hematology, oncology)</li>
                    <li>Call subspecialists when questions arise</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- SLIDE 9 -->
        <div class="slide">
            <h1>CLL & Infection Risk</h1>
            
            <div class="critical-box">
                <h3>Why CLL Patients Are Immunocompromised</h3>
            </div>
            
            <div class="box">
                <h3>1. Hypogammaglobulinemia (50-80% of patients)</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Decreased antibody production</li>
                    <li>Risk: <em>S. pneumoniae, H. influenzae</em> (encapsulated organisms)</li>
                    <li>Most common cause of infection in CLL</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="box">
                <h3>2. T-cell Dysfunction</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>Impaired cell-mediated immunity</li>
                    <li>Risk: Viral infections, intracellular bacteria</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="box">
                <h3>3. Neutropenia</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>From disease or treatment</li>
                    <li>Risk: Bacterial and fungal infections</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="critical-box" style="margin-top: 30px;">
                <h3>Critical Recognition</h3>
                <p style="font-size: 1.3em; font-weight: bold;">
                    Infection is the LEADING cause of morbidity and mortality in CLL
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li>Pneumonia is most common infection</li>
                    <li>Recurrent sinopulmonary infections typical</li>
                    <li>Both typical and opportunistic pathogens possible</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
            
            <div class="box">
                <h3>Management for Hospitalized CLL Patients</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Check immunoglobulins:</strong> IgG, IgA, IgM</li>
                    <li><strong>IVIG candidate?</strong> If IgG <500 + recurrent infections</li>
                    <li><strong>PJP prophylaxis:</strong> TMP-SMX if CD4 <200 or on treatment</li>
                    <li><strong>Longer antibiotic course:</strong> 7-10 days vs 5 days</li>
                    <li><strong>Coordinate with hematology</strong></li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- SLIDE 10 -->
        <div class="slide">
            <h1>Key Takeaways</h1>
            
            <div class="box">
                <h3>1. Comprehensive Chart Review Is Essential</h3>
                <p>Use the SEARCH mnemonic. Critical information is usually in the chart - you just need to find it systematically.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="box">
                <h3>2. CLL = Immunocompromised, Always</h3>
                <p>Infection is leading cause of morbidity. Check IgG levels, consider prophylaxis, coordinate with hematology.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="box">
                <h3>3. Clinical Picture > Laboratory Values</h3>
                <p>IDSA: Clinical stability = treatment success. WBC normalization not required. Always check CBC differential.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="box">
                <h3>4. Stewardship Applies to All Patients</h3>
                <p>Appropriate empiric therapy. Avoid unnecessary escalation in improving patients. Standard CAP: 5 days if stable.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="box">
                <h3>5. Care Coordination Matters</h3>
                <p>Contact established subspecialists. This patient missed his hematology appointment because he was hospitalized - his hematologist didn't know.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="box">
                <h3>6. Systems Thinking Prevents Future Gaps</h3>
                <p>Multiple factors contribute to information gaps. Focus on system improvements, not individual blame. Learn from every case.</p>
            </div>
            
            <div class="critical-box" style="margin-top: 40px; text-align: center;">
                <h2>Focus on Learning and Systems Improvement</h2>
                <p style="font-size: 1.2em; margin-top: 15px;">
                    Excellence in medicine requires both individual diligence and robust systems that support comprehensive care
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="nav-buttons">
        <button id="prev" onclick="changeSlide(-1)">← Previous</button>
        <button id="next" onclick="changeSlide(1)">Next →</button>
    </div>

    <script>
        let current = 0;
        const slides = document.querySelectorAll('.slide');
        const total = slides.length;
        
        document.getElementById('total').textContent = total;
        
        function showSlide(n) {
            slides[current].classList.remove('active');
            current = (n + total) % total;
            slides[current].classList.add('active');
            
            document.getElementById('current').textContent = current + 1;
            document.getElementById('prev').disabled = (current === 0);
            document.getElementById('next').disabled = (current === total - 1);
            
            window.scrollTo(0, 0);
        }
        
        function changeSlide(dir) {
            showSlide(current + dir);
        }
        
        // Keyboard navigation
        document.addEventListener('keydown', (e) => {
            if (e.key === 'ArrowLeft') changeSlide(-1);
            if (e.key === 'ArrowRight') changeSlide(1);
        });
        
        // Touch swipe for iPad
        let startX = 0;
        document.addEventListener('touchstart', (e) => {
            startX = e.touches[0].clientX;
        });
        
        document.addEventListener('touchend', (e) => {
            let endX = e.changedTouches[0].clientX;
            if (startX - endX > 50) changeSlide(1);
            if (endX - startX > 50) changeSlide(-1);
        });
        
        showSlide(0);
    </script>
</body>
</html>
